#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: upstream/content/blog/2021/04/camel-k-140-Whatsnew/index.md:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Apache Camel K 1.4.0 What's New"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/content/blog/2021/04/camel-k-140-Whatsnew/index.md:10
#, no-wrap
msgid "Apache Camel K 1.4.0 has just been released!\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/content/blog/2021/04/camel-k-140-Whatsnew/index.md:13
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"This is a new major release of Camel K with an improved stability over previous versions, but also adding new features\n"
"that simplify the overall user experience.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/content/blog/2021/04/camel-k-140-Whatsnew/index.md:15
#, no-wrap
msgid "It is based on Camel 3.9.0 and Camel-Quarkus 1.8.1, providing all improvements that they bring, plus much more. In this blog post, we're going to describe the most important changes.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: upstream/content/blog/2021/04/camel-k-140-Whatsnew/index.md:16
#, no-wrap
msgid "Embedded Kamelet catalog"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/content/blog/2021/04/camel-k-140-Whatsnew/index.md:19
#, no-wrap
msgid "Camel K 1.4.0 comes with an embedded [Kamelet catalog](/camel-kamelets/latest/) containing multiple connectors ready for use.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/content/blog/2021/04/camel-k-140-Whatsnew/index.md:21
#, no-wrap
msgid "When installing the operator into a namespace (but also globally in the cluster), the operator installs all the kamelets from the catalog ([version 0.2.1](https://github.com/apache/camel-kamelets/tree/v0.2.1)), so that any integration can use them directly.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/content/blog/2021/04/camel-k-140-Whatsnew/index.md:23
#, no-wrap
msgid "Users can bind them to a specific destination by writing a YAML binding file, as explained in the [specific documentation related to each Kamelet](/camel-kamelets/latest/aws-sqs-source.html#_knative_source).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/content/blog/2021/04/camel-k-140-Whatsnew/index.md:25
#, no-wrap
msgid "Or, you can use the new `kamel bind` command (see below).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/content/blog/2021/04/camel-k-140-Whatsnew/index.md:27
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Note:** it's easy to write your own Kamelet and publish it to the Apache Catalog. Take a look at the [Kamelets developer guide](/camel-k/latest/kamelets/kamelets-dev.html).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: upstream/content/blog/2021/04/camel-k-140-Whatsnew/index.md:28
#, no-wrap
msgid "Kamel bind command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/content/blog/2021/04/camel-k-140-Whatsnew/index.md:31
#, no-wrap
msgid "We've added a `bind` subcommand to the  `kamel` CLI that provides a new way to use Kamelets directly when you need to connect them to Knative channels, Kafka topics and any other endpoint.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/content/blog/2021/04/camel-k-140-Whatsnew/index.md:33
#, no-wrap
msgid "E.g. Suppose that you want to get events of earthquakes happening around the world, as JSON objects, in your Knative channel named `earthquakes`. All you need to do is to install Camel K on your cluster and then execute the following command:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: upstream/content/blog/2021/04/camel-k-140-Whatsnew/index.md:34
#, no-wrap
msgid "kamel bind earthquake-source channel:earthquakes\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/content/blog/2021/04/camel-k-140-Whatsnew/index.md:40
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"This command creates the KameletBinding resource for you and the Camel K operator does the rest to bring that data into your channel.\n"
"Data is produced using the [Earthquake Source](/camel-kamelets/latest/earthquake-source.html) Kamelet available in the embedded Katalog.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/content/blog/2021/04/camel-k-140-Whatsnew/index.md:42
#, no-wrap
msgid "You can use any other Kamelet from the catalog using the `kamel bind` command.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/content/blog/2021/04/camel-k-140-Whatsnew/index.md:44
#, no-wrap
msgid "You can also target any other Kubernetes reference that is supported by Camel K, for example, sink into a [Strimzi KafkaTopic](https://strimzi.io/), using a fully qualified reference, for example:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: upstream/content/blog/2021/04/camel-k-140-Whatsnew/index.md:45
#, no-wrap
msgid "kamel bind earthquake-source kafka.strimzi.io/v1beta1:KafkaTopic:mytopic\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/content/blog/2021/04/camel-k-140-Whatsnew/index.md:50
#, no-wrap
msgid "Of course, the command also supports plain Camel URIs, which are useful especially when you're developing a new Kamelet. For example, you can write:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: upstream/content/blog/2021/04/camel-k-140-Whatsnew/index.md:51
#, no-wrap
msgid "kamel bind earthquake-source log:info?showHeaders=true\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/content/blog/2021/04/camel-k-140-Whatsnew/index.md:56
#, no-wrap
msgid "And the command will create a binding that just prints to the log the JSON data produced by the source.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: upstream/content/blog/2021/04/camel-k-140-Whatsnew/index.md:57
#, no-wrap
msgid "Kamel dump command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/content/blog/2021/04/camel-k-140-Whatsnew/index.md:61
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"When users have issues understanding why Camel K is not behaving as expected, they often need to provide useful information \n"
"about the current state of their cluster, to let Camel K developers investigate the issue and provide a solution or a quick workaround (e.g. in a Github issue, or in the Zulip chat).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/content/blog/2021/04/camel-k-140-Whatsnew/index.md:63
#, no-wrap
msgid "Usually, to identify the root cause of an issue, developers need to know things like:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: upstream/content/blog/2021/04/camel-k-140-Whatsnew/index.md:69
#, no-wrap
msgid "What routes the user is trying to run\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: upstream/content/blog/2021/04/camel-k-140-Whatsnew/index.md:69
#, no-wrap
msgid "What the Camel K operator is doing\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: upstream/content/blog/2021/04/camel-k-140-Whatsnew/index.md:69
#, no-wrap
msgid "What images have been built, which versions of all libraries are they using\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: upstream/content/blog/2021/04/camel-k-140-Whatsnew/index.md:69
#, no-wrap
msgid "What's the state of the Camel K custom resources\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: upstream/content/blog/2021/04/camel-k-140-Whatsnew/index.md:69
#, no-wrap
msgid "What errors do Camel K integration throw when they start\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/content/blog/2021/04/camel-k-140-Whatsnew/index.md:71
#, no-wrap
msgid "Providing such information has always been hard, but we now have a quick way to obtain all that.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: upstream/content/blog/2021/04/camel-k-140-Whatsnew/index.md:72
#, no-wrap
msgid "kamel dump status.log\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/content/blog/2021/04/camel-k-140-Whatsnew/index.md:79
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"This simple command will store in a text file all the information needed to investigate a possible issue in the cluster.\n"
"The user can now *edit the file to remove sensitive information* (which the command may not be able to tell apart), then \n"
"share it with developers to have much better insights.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: upstream/content/blog/2021/04/camel-k-140-Whatsnew/index.md:80
#, no-wrap
msgid "Stability and compatibility"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/content/blog/2021/04/camel-k-140-Whatsnew/index.md:83
#, no-wrap
msgid "We focused a lot on stability and improved compatibility with other tools of the ecosystem.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/content/blog/2021/04/camel-k-140-Whatsnew/index.md:87
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"**Knative support** (0.22.0) has been improved by fixing compatibility issues that sometimes caused multiple revisions\n"
"to be present for the same service. We've also changed the way channels and brokers are bound to the integrations. Now it's possible\n"
"to bind integrations to multiple channels and even create sequences of integrations attached to channels without any issue (e.g. [#2190](https://github.com/apache/camel-k/pull/2190), [#2115](https://github.com/apache/camel-k/pull/2115)).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/content/blog/2021/04/camel-k-140-Whatsnew/index.md:90
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"We've improved **installation options**, letting you configure things that may be important in a production environment, like [setting toleration](https://github.com/apache/camel-k/pull/2114) or using a [secured maven repository](https://github.com/apache/camel-k/pull/2180).\n"
"At the same time, we've fixed compatibility with recent dev environments, e.g. letting you [smoothly install Camel K in K3S](/camel-k/latest/installation/registry/k3s.html).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/content/blog/2021/04/camel-k-140-Whatsnew/index.md:92
#, no-wrap
msgid "We also kept doing changes to continuously improve speed. On the runtime side of Camel K, we now use the [Quarkus fast-jar format](https://github.com/apache/camel-k/pull/1931) to reduce boot times. And last but not least on the operator side, it's possible to install Camel K globally in a cluster and have much faster build times by [sharing base images across the cluster](https://github.com/apache/camel-k/pull/2058).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/content/blog/2021/04/camel-k-140-Whatsnew/index.md:93
#, no-wrap
msgid "The list of important changes in the [1.4.0 release](https://github.com/apache/camel-k/releases/tag/v1.4.0) is too long for this blog post. There have **never been so many contributors** as in this release and we **thank them all for their awesome work!**\n"
msgstr ""
